## Description: What is it? (max 1,500 characters)

This is a guide that offers a comprehensive introduction to the principles and practices of prototyping. It outlines the scenarios where prototyping is advantageous, provides practical  guidance on the methodologies and techniques involved, and elucidates  the underlying reasons for adopting prototyping as a strategy forservice innovation and improvement.

## Purpose: Why do we use this method or tool for R&amp;D? (max 1,500 characters)

Prototyping is an approach to developing and testing ideas at an early stage before large-scale resources are committed to implementation. Prototyping in the public sector's domain offers a dynamic and effective approach to innovation, enabling the private and public sector to develop and  test ideas, engage stakeholders collaboratively, explore  alternative solutions, and iterate based on feedback and learning.

## Summary: Describe in one sentence, what it is and what it does? (max 120 characters)

This is a guide that provides an introduction to prototyping, explaining when you might do it, how and why.

## Instructions: How is it used for R&amp;D? What steps to follow?

The guide provides the theory and the framework provide step-by-step guidance on how to apply it in real-world settings.

## Requirements: What is needed to effectively use it for R&amp;D? (e.g. skills, conditions, inputs, resources)

The Prototyping Framework that accompanies this resource provides a guide to activities that you can follow to get started on prototyping.

While prototyping may still be relatively uncommon in public service contexts, there is a growing recognition of its value and relevance.  Embracing a culture of experimentation and learning is essential formainstreaming prototyping within service development processes.

## Description: What is it? (max 1,500 characters)

They are two  solar mobile kiosks prototypes using for conservation of perishable products. One is designed for street youths offering street eatery services and another one is designed for women saling fruits and vegetables.

## Purpose: Why do we use this method or tool for R&amp;D? (max 1,500 characters)

Prototyping is used for R&amp;D, because by creating a physical or digital model befor the main tool, it is possible to gather user feedback and understand if this can solve their problem. Prototyping also save time and money by identifying issues early on, thus avoiding costly changes of a scale development.

## Summary: Describe in one sentence, what it is and what it does? (max 120 characters)

Prototyping allows us to see what the final product will look like and to adjust it before scaling it up if it meets the expected requirements.

## Instructions: How is it used for R&amp;D? What steps to follow?

The prototyping is used for R&amp;D to test and refine an idea or a product. For our experiment, we followed these steps:  
  
  
  
  
Step 1: Learn more about the difficulties facing those  
actors through a survey  
  
Step 2: Improving specification of requirements  
and prototyping  
  
Step 3: Testing of the prototypes  
  
Step 4: Capture essons learned

## Requirements: What is needed to effectively use it for R&amp;D? (e.g. skills, conditions, inputs, resources)

For effective R&amp;D, The following conditions appear to be necessary, if you want to use prototyping:  
  
  
Clear Objectives: Define what you want to achieve with the prototype. This could be testing a concept, exploring design options, or validating technical feasibility.  
Cross-Disciplinary Team: Assemble a small team with diverse skills, including design, engineering, and user experience, to contribute different perspectives to the prototype.  
Iterative Process: Be prepared to iterate on the design. Prototyping is an iterative or agile  process where feedback leads to refinements and improvements.  
Resource Allocation: Ensure you have the necessary resources, which could include time, budget, materials, and tools, to create and test the prototype.  
Evaluation Metrics: Establish criteria for evaluating the prototype’s performance. This  
will help in assessing its success and areas that need work.
